9 FLOOR SUBSTITUTE
10 An Act relating to court reporters; amending 20 O.S.
2021, Sections 106.4, as amended by Section 1,
11 Chapter 100, O.S.L. 2023, and 106.9, as last amended
by Section 1, Chapter 263, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp.
12 2025, Sections 106.4 and 106.9), which relate to
court reporter duties and salaries; expanding
13 allowable means of court reporting; authorizing
certain remote availability; providing requirements
14 and authorizations for ordering transcripts;
clarifying language; increasing certain annual
15 salary; increasing number of certifications eligible
for certain payments; modifying continuing education
16 requirements; providing for suspension and
ineligibility for payments under certain conditions;
17 updating statutory language; amending 20 O.S. 2021,
Section 1503, which relates to shorthand reporter
18 examinations for certifications; modifying allowable
methods of shorthand reporting; providing an
19 effective date; and declaring an emergency.
20
21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
22 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 106.4, as
23 amended by Section 1, Chapter 100, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp. 2025,
24 Section 106.4), is amended to read as follows:
Req. No. 3979 Page 1

1 Section 106.4. A. 1. The court reporter shall make a full
2 reporting by means of stenographic hand, steno-mask or, stenographic
3 machine notes, any other method of reporting authorized by the
4 Supreme Court, or a combination thereof, of all proceedings,
5 including the statements of counsel and the court and the evidence,
6 in trials and other judicial proceedings to which the court reporter
7 is assigned by the appointing judge unless excused by the judge who
8 is trying the case with the consent of the parties to the action.
9 Nothing herein contained shall be construed to authorize the
10 certification of persons as certified shorthand reporters who rely
11 exclusively upon the steno-mask for reporting judicial proceedings,
12 except as provided by law. A refusal of the court to permit or to
13 require any statement to be taken down by the court reporter or
14 transcribed after being taken down, upon the same being shown by
15 affidavit or other direct and competent evidence, to the Supreme
16 Court, or other appellate court, shall constitute a denial of due
17 process of law. The court reporter may use an electronic instrument
18 as a supplementary device.
19 2. In any trial, hearing or proceedings, if no court reporter
20 is available to the assigned judge either remotely or in person:
21 a. the judge before whom the matter is being heard may
22 order the proceedings electronically recorded and a
23 trial or proceedings may proceed without the necessity
24 of a court reporter being present. Provided that if
Req. No. 3979 Page 2

1 an official transcript is ordered then it shall be
2 prepared by the official court reporter Any party may
3 order a transcript, provided that for use in any
4 subsequent trial, hearing, proceeding, or appeal, only
5 official transcripts prepared by an official court
6 reporter are permitted for any purpose, or
7 b. with approval of the judge, the parties may stipulate
8 to the use of a freelance reporter and share the cost.
9 If ordered, the transcript shall be prepared by the
10 approved reporter and shall be considered the official
11 transcript for all purposes.
12 B. 1. Upon request of either party in a civil or criminal
13 case, the reporter shall transcribe the proceedings in a trial or
14 other judicial proceeding, or so much thereof as may be requested by
15 the party, certify to the correctness of the transcript, and deliver
16 the same in accordance with the rules of the Supreme Court. The fee
17 for an original transcript shall be set by the Supreme Court. Two
18 copies of the original transcript shall be furnished without
19 additional charge. Each page shall be at least twenty-five lines to
20 the page and typed no fewer than nine characters to the typed inch.
21 Each page shall be no more than double spaced and the margin on the
22 left side of the page shall be no more than one and one-half (1 1/2)
23 inches and the margin on the right side of the page shall be no more
24 than one-half (1/2) inch from the edge of the paper. The format for
Req. No. 3979 Page 3

1 all transcripts shall be prescribed by the Supreme Court. The fees
2 for making the transcript shall be paid in the first instance by the
3 party requesting the transcript and shall be taxed as costs in the
4 suit.
5 2. When the judge on his or her own motion orders a transcript
6 of the reporter’s notes, the judge may direct the payment of charges
7 and the taxation of the charges as costs in such manner as the court
8 deems appropriate. In a criminal action, if the defendant shall
9 present to the judge an affidavit that the defendant intends in good
10 faith to take an appeal in the case and that a transcript of the
11 reporter’s notes is necessary to enable the defendant to prosecute
12 the appeal, and that he or she has not the means to pay for the
13 transcript, the court, upon finding that there is reasonable basis
14 for the averment, shall order the transcript made at the expense of
15 the district court fund. The format preparation, delivery, and
16 filing of transcripts to be used in civil and criminal appeals may
17 be regulated by the Supreme Court.
18 C. The court reporter shall file his or her records of the
19 evidence and the proceedings taken in any case with the clerk of the
20 court in which the case was tried.
21 D. To the extent that it does not substantially interfere with
22 the court reporter’s other official duties, the judge by whom a
23 reporter is employed or to whom he or she is assigned may assign a
24
Req. No. 3979 Page 4

1 repo rter to secretarial or clerical duties arising out of official
2 court operations.
3 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 20 O.S. 2021, Section 106.9, as
4 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 263, O.S.L. 2023 (20 O.S. Supp.
5 2025, Section 106.9), is amended to read as follows:
6 Section 106.9. A. Each court reporter regularly engaged by the
7 district court, the Workers’ Compensation Court of Existing Claims,
8 or the Corporation Commission shall be paid a salary pursuant to the
9 salary schedule established by the annual appropriation for the
10 district courts and Corporation Commission and in accordance with
11 the job description for the position to which appointed. For fiscal
12 year 2023 and each fiscal year thereafter, each court reporter shall
13 receive an annual salary of Fifty-three Thousand Dollars
14 ($53,000.00) Sixty-five Thousand Dollars ($65,000.00).
15 B. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
16 who are certified or licensed shorthand reporters and those acting
17 shorthand reporters pursuant to paragraph 3 of Section 106.3B of
18 this title shall be paid annually the sum of Four Hundred Dollars
19 ($400.00) for each year of service to the district court, the
20 Workers’ Compensation Court, the Workers’ Compensation Court of
21 Existing Claims and the Corporation Commission, with a maximum of
22 twenty (20) years of service only to be used for the purpose of
23 longevity, not to exceed Eight Thousand Dollars ($8,000.00) per
24 year, payable monthly. For the purpose of payment for longevity,
Req. No. 3979 Page 5

1 “yea rs of service” is defined as all years served as a certified or
2 licensed court reporter in the district court, the Workers’
3 Compensation Court, the Workers’ Compensation Court of Existing
4 Claims and the Corporation Commission after June 30, 1978.
5 Longevity payments shall be made on July 1 of each year following
6 completion of the first year of service as defined herein.
7 C. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
8 eligible for longevity payments pursuant to subsection B of this
9 section shall be paid an annual equipment allowance of Three
10 Thousand Dollars ($3,000.00). Payments for such allowance shall be
11 made on July 1 of each year following completion of the first year
12 of service as defined in subsection B of this section.
13 D. In addition to their base salaries, official court reporters
14 who are certified shorthand reporters shall be paid the following:
15 1. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
16 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is holds one or
17 more of the following certifications:
18 a. a Registered Professional Reporter (RPR), as
19 recognized by the State Board of Examiners of
20 Certified Shorthand Reporters. To qualify as a RPR,
21 an official court reporter shall have National Court
22 Reporters Association (NCRA),
23 b. a Certified Verbatim Reporter (CVR), as recognized by
24 the National Verbatim Reporters Association (NVRA),
Req. No. 3979 Page 6

1 c. a Certified Verbatim Reporter – Stenotype (CVR-S), as
2 recognized by the National Verbatim Reporters
3 Association (NVRA), or
4 d. other certifications authorized by the Supreme Court
5 that demonstrate a proficiency level in reporting
6 testimony and proceedings of a speed of not less than
7 two hundred twenty-five (225) words per minute in
8 taking a question-and-answer-type dictation, two
9 hundred (200) words per minute in taking a jury
10 charge, and one hundred eighty (180) words per minute
11 in taking literary material,. In addition, the
12 individual shall pass a the Oklahoma Written Knowledge
13 Test with a score of at least seventy percent (70%),
14 all as determined by an examination recognized by the
15 Board, and shall complete thirty (30) hours of
16 continuing education per three-year cycle commencing
17 at the date of recognition as directed by the Supreme
18 Court;
19 2. The sum of Two Thousand Dollars ($2,000.00) per year,
20 payable monthly, to any official court reporter who is holds one or
21 more of the following certifications:
22 a. a Registered Merit Reporter (RMR), as recognized by
23 the State Board of Examiners of Certified Shorthand
24 Reporters. To qualify as a RMR, an official court
